vectorData.altText: 18. The _________________ nerve is most closely associated with the surgical neck of the humerus.
That's right! The axillary nerve is closely associated with the surgical neck of the humerus, therefore injury to the area may lead to nerve damage.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Some peripheral nerves, at certain points during their course through the upper limb, are closely applied to bone. Traumatic injury in these areas can result in nerve damage with stereotyped motor and sensory signs     .
The axillary nerve is closely associated with the surgical neck of the humerus and is vulnerable here. While this is the most common site of humeral fracture, which may damage the axillary nerve, the nerve is more commonly damaged with a dislocation of the glenohumeral joint.
In the arm, the radial nerve runs obliquely across the posterior aspect of humerus along the spiral (radial) groove, and the radial nerve is vulnerable here, in fractures of the midshaft of the humerus.
At the elbow, the ulnar nerve passes posterior to the medial epicondyle, where it is vulnerable to fracture or compression.
i.e. the motor and sensory signs of peripheral nerve damage are predictable, if you know the functions of the nerves.
